<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#871f78">Originally posted by Thece on 11-07-2000 08:56 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Gordon makes the assumption that all people who play EQ do so with the one intent of making the highest level they can with a single character.  But the problem with that assumption is that not everyone plays to get to 60.  Simplifying the game into a race to level 60 just makes it easier to ignore a large majority of the player population to continue to cater to their powergamers and high levels.  

It isn't a matter of high levels running out of places to hunt - it's not like the old days where everyone packed into LGuk like sardines. It's a matter of the high level gamers getting bored of the places they have.  So why is it not okay that lower levels get bored of the places they have too?

I've been playing this game since release and have never had a single character over level 45.  I don't like the way the game changes at the high levels, it seems to become about items and not exploration.  The senority systems and powerguilds stink. I'm simply not willing to play like that.

I have a group of friends I play with who all play the same way, we tend to quit and start new characters all the time.  I have met many others who prefer the mid-levels to the high levels as well.  So I guess us getting bored with the same 'ol zones and creatures just isn't as important as those level 60s getting bored of Veeshan's.   :(</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
